segments.text: In the beginning, it was easy to get the entire community to participate because they were the pioneers and they had that sense of excitement of being involved in something that was very new and starting it.
And one of the things that was done was to have luminarias on every driveway and road and front yard on Christmas Eve.
And using my street again as a good example, there is probably a third of the residents

that are original purchasers the resale second or third or fourth time resale homeowner who has not been to the information center who has not watched the woodlands grow and been here from those early days doesn't know why somebody's knocking on their door saying we need six dollars for the luminarias for christmas eve and all the
Experienced veteran residents know, oh, that's for the luminaries, and the whole community does it.

And so now the challenge is to maintain that small feeling or that sense of community when we've got 30,000 people so that we don't become one of those subdivisions, if you will, where people don't have that sense of loyalty.
How does that challenge be managed?
The WCA, the Woodlands Community Association, is the one, the best source to help organize the different villages and get a community-wide effort going or maintain it.
Currently, you'll talk to people, I'm sure, that are gonna talk about this year's effort in recycling.
The club has been formed
WCA has negotiated with Western Waste to do some curbside pickup of recyclables on a test basis to see how the thing can work.
We have two local newspapers.
That helps to get the word out.
Again, going back to the problem of size, the YMCA, the Little League program,
the churches, the grocery store, when everything was smaller, you kept running into familiar faces at every turn.
Now, you see many people that you just don't see very often, and I can feel it, and I'm certain those that have been here longer than five and a half years can feel it as well.
that that's going to be a real challenge for us to maintain that very strong loyalty and sense of community that the Woodlands has.
The lighting of the doves is a good example where we shut down the road here and have several thousands of people come and watch the lighting of the doves before Christmas time.
You can go to that and see a lot of people that you just didn't see at Little League or soccer or
or church or the grocery store.
And you know they live here.
And in that regard, I think what will happen is each generation of homebuyer will have their sense of community.
And as we go ever further to the west and to the north as we develop,
will have sub-neighborhoods within the woodlands where they may have a particular bond with one another.
And there will be a sense of sub-community within the woodlands.
I would think it's overly sanguine to expect, in a community of 30,000 people, which may double in 10 years, that people are going to say the woodlands as a possessive.
They may say Grogan's Mill as a possessive, or some other government.
I don't think that's going to happen.
And in a way, we've unconsciously done that.
What I'm trying to say is that we've somewhat synchronized the construction activity in
in a sizable portion of the new home offering.
And what I'm trying to say is one of the areas that we did in North Panther Creek had village weekly life forms, the smaller custom and the medium sized custom homes.
We had 600 home sales all take place within a two year period, all in one general vicinity.

in the past many times we would have had the custom activity finishing up in one area while the production housing was starting up in a new area and we had sort of leapfrogged with production first and then custom later and you had some lag of one or two or three years before a particular 30-40 acre section got developed and so you really
You never got everybody moving in all at one time and then all the construction being finished all at one time and the project be finished.
And I think that just as things have worked out, partly because of the pace that we were fortunate enough to enjoy where we were selling 600, 700, 800 a year, you can go in and finish something.
I think we got out of that pattern in the early 80s because
The plan was certainly to finish as quickly as possible, but the market wasn't there, and so the sales slowed down, and it just didn't work out.
You mentioned this was accidental.
Having recognized the advantage of doing that, is that now going to be a built-in element?
It's as much as, boy, to the extent the market will let us do it, absolutely.
Because if there's one thing that upsets current residents,
It's the activity of subcontractors on their property while building a home next door.
From trash to debris and beer bottles or whatever, it's a problem for the developer to keep the existing resident happy with respect to radios blaring at 6 in the morning.
It's not a pleasant experience to have a home built next door to your home or a block away for that matter.
And that's been one of the sort of fringe benefits of this pace that we've enjoyed.
We really get in and out of a neighborhood.
You know, the trucks are off the street and people, you know, the sandwich pickups aren't coming up and down the street.
It's a better street.
It's a better environment.
Do you work with the builders as well?
I don't work directly with them.
Ted Nelson is the director of lot sales and he's
deals one-on-one with them in terms of putting the lots under contract and day-to-day negotiations, if you will.
I just wondered, because the other side of the story you're telling me is that, yes, we worked hard with the realtors, yes, we worked hard with the companies and residents, future and past.
How have we worked with the builders to... All right, let me go back to that.
Maybe this is a longer story than I realized, but
One of the other things that was clear to me in 1985, and that was that the Woodlands home designs were woefully out of date.
All of my experience prior to coming up here had been on the west side of Houston.
And at that time, in the new homes, by and large, you had to have, in order to be competitive

the glass showers in the master baths, or the Jennier cook range in the kitchen, or an island in the kitchen, the atrium windows over the kitchen window, or skylights, 10-foot ceilings, plant ledges, a whole lot of excitement on the interior of the home.
And I got here, and the kitchens were small, the cabinet count was small,
They didn't have sizable kitchen family living room arrangements.
The designs were out of date.
Ted Nelson and I took it upon ourselves to go and find some new builders or try to get the existing builders to change.
I think we turned over about 50% of the new home builder group.
Some of them wisely said, I've made a lot of money and I'm not going to
try and build homes in the late 80s.
And they kept their money.
What do you mean by that?
You mean they said, we're not going to play?
They just said, I just don't want to risk my money.
I don't want to be a home builder in the 80s, in the last half of the 80s.
I think I'm done.
And whatever their goal was, they picked up their marbles and went home.
Fortunately, those who stayed and the ones that we've since recruited
have come here and brought new designs, sat down with the salespeople and said, tell us what the buyers are asking for.
We then encouraged them to provide a minimum number of inventory of homes.
And we said, you've got to have this many homes in inventory for the springtime, prime buying season.
We've got all this work going on with Wanda Mason and the Relo companies and the realtor community promising
that we're going to have plenty of new home inventory.
We're looking to you to provide it, and we're also looking to you to provide what's going to sell.
And we really, I think the numbers are like 85 or 90 homes in 85 that were custom, and then it grew to about 125.
Today we're at about a third are custom, and they steadily grew.
120, 152, 250, and on up to about three this year.
So we changed what the homebuyers saw when they got here.
And we changed some of our planning to accommodate a little bit wider lot.
There's a big demand.
One of the big things, especially with the number of out-of-town buyers who came from a community where they had a basement, there's no basement.
So we have a third garage whenever possible.
because they have the need for the space to put their stuff in.

So a little bit wider garage, a little bit deeper garage, and then just all of those things I mentioned about higher ceilings and all the other do-why gadgets in the house has really created an exciting group of homes to come and look at, and they'll showcase the homes that we do every spring.
Has brought some new and innovative stuff
And so that has helped the pace of new home sales, obviously.
So we changed what was being offered as well.
And that was another good strategic move, was to go out and get the right stuff to be built.
So we did some internal things and paid a lot of attention to the external things.
Now the big challenge for 1991 is going to be, will the people coming from the east or west coast be able to sell their house?
Yeah.
I'm running out of time.
You're running out of time.
But that's something I want to explore a little bit.
What does the future hold for the woodlands?
That's one thing I want you to think about, not just in the short term, but also maybe through the year 2000 and beyond.
Because one of the things I'm looking at
George Mitchell, whose vision and personality is stamped all over the place, is 72.
The Woodlands obviously isn't going to tap out at 150,000 until a good 25, 30 years, not really more.
In fact, that's one of the things about his vision that is so intriguing, is he's planning for things which he will never see.
Oh, really?
Is he planning that?
I don't know.
Yeah, that's true.
He may, like God, strides the world and thinks he will never die.
But what I'm curious about, though, is what challenges do you foresee, perceive?
How successful do you think that vision will be with the possible exit of Mr. Mitchell?
How enduring is that vision?
How baked into the infrastructure is that vision?
Those kinds of questions.
There is, to my knowledge,
no public or private document that talks about what happens after that date.
Mr. Mitchell's not personally addressing our focus.
So it's just my hunch.
My hunch is that he will have put in place some mechanism whereby his desires will be adhered to.
In terms of

the good feeling that people have about the Woodlands people live here now I think it will keep that good feeling as I said where we moved in 600 people in two years to one area will continue to have that good feeling on on a small sub community level but I think that one of the things that the

the scope of things that unite the people in the woodlands will adjust to the the growth and the one example that i'm thinking about right now to try to explain what i mean by those words is the pavilion you can't have a pavilion that holds 11 000 people and doing a community-wide event if you've only got 11 000 people if you've got 30 000 people now you can
deal with the scale and scope of a facility like the pavilion.
The mall, I'm sure, will have events that will be suitable for a community of 60,000 or 90,000 or whatever the final number may be.
And he may have visions of things beyond that.
I don't know.
But whenever...
The planning number I heard is 100 and a half.
Oh, yeah.
But what I'm saying is I don't know what facility...
would balance with a community of that size.
Is it another mall?
Is it a hyper mall?
Is it like the one in Canada with the Walt Disney thing under one roof?
I don't know.
But the concept of, in a way, not in a way, but very dramatically, the shift to the focus on the environment could make Mr. Mitchell appear to be more of a genius than he is.
because if you go back to the 70s when the Woodlands was launched and you remember a John Denver and the anti-establishment kind of feeling, this was a real progressive thing.
To me, that's one of the marketing challenges we have is in its day, the Woodlands was very new, made a major break from the development community standards of its day.
Today, friends of mine that work for other developers have caught up

on paper they all have hike and bike trails they all have amenities they all on paper will read a master plan community our challenge is going to be how to get different from our competition as it exists today again and still adhere to the natural look
the mix of different housing styles in one neighborhood, I think those things will happen.
But the challenge is already being met, though, in a way.
Mr. Mitchell and Marty Souter,
Dominic Lamb, there's a bunch of people who are in fact addressing issues that King would never address.
The vision is a distinct vision.
That is, let's have a lot of people, a significant proportion, maybe even a third of the people working in the woodlands.
We drive five minutes and they're at work.
They can go home for lunch.
That kind of thing is novel.
Absolutely.
My crystal ball gets real foggy when you talk about

fifty thousand plus I think that what we have achieved from the residential standpoint and the balance of housing and the pace of 900 or so a year is a is a bit of a plateau and a good one and a comfortable one and
We hope to do a little bit better than that in terms of our 25-year projections.
Will the time ever come when you guys are held back so that, in fact, the job creating element can catch up?
There's an incipient danger.
in this community in that it could turn into another development.
If, in fact, those jobs don't come online, it becomes another Kingwood in a way.
Again, going back to external factors and their effect on our success, one of the other major ones that I left out was the tollway system in Houston.
And to answer what you've just addressed about internal job growth,
I'd submit that the Sam Houston Tollway and Hardy Toll Road will provide, they're already providing, homebuyers who work in far west Houston because they want to be with trees.
And I would say that all the mega plans that exist for mass transportation in Houston, that even without internal job growth,
the home sales will be there because the transportation will be improved to the point that we'll be able to accommodate the commuter better.
That I understand.
My concern was in terms of how much commitment, I guess, is what I'm asking.
Is there to the holistic, philosophical basis upon which the Woodlands was created?
That is, that it is in fact a hometown, that people work here, they play here, they live here.
Do you see what I'm saying?
And when one gets out of balance with the other, or isn't even close, or will that even be allowed to happen?
That's a good question for somebody else.
My only comment would be that the amount of money that has been and is being invested in the job creation side, I would venture to say it's unrealistic to think that we would abandon that.
That's kind of what you're calling for.
I agree.
If it doesn't work, will we abandon it?
I think that's not one of the choices.

No, that wasn't in a way, but I also wondered, will you be allowed to grow at the rates which you can grow, given the tollway access, when the philosophical underpinnings of the woodlands get undermined because it becomes really a residential community?
Too normal?
Yeah, too normal.
Too normal?
Yeah.
I don't know.
That's a good question.
I don't know.
Of course, you probably wouldn't decide that anyway.
Yeah.
I've got to go.
Okay.
Good, because I can't answer the question.
